default&#xa0;default3.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRotary aviation is a highly regulated sector. All operations are overseen by the UK Civil Aviation Authority (UK CAA). Each operator holds an Air Operator Certificate (AOC) issued by the UK CAA. To secure an AOC, operators go through rigorous scrutiny and audits of their procedures, people, assets, and systems. We also provide evidence of how we prioritise the safety of our people and passengers above all else. This certificate approves the operators to provide commercial passenger flights for the oil and gas industry.
default&#xa0;
default3.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn addition, airworthiness is underpinned by strict compliance procedures laid down by the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA). The Agency promotes common standards of safety and environmental protection in Europe and worldwide. It provides for a single European market in the aviation industry. 
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs well as the UK CAA and EASA regulations, operators are 
defaultobliged to comply with OGP standards for helicopter operations. We are also 
defaultsubject to the contractual requirements of our customers, which often include customer-specific aviation standards (e.g. a minimum number of flight hours before a pilot can fly offshore). Although most standards are routinely met by all operators, there can be significant 
defaultadditional 
defaultvariations. An operator with 10 clients, for example, might be expected to operate flights to 10 different standards. And, as each customer company has its own standard, each must conduct its own audits. 
default&#xa0;
default3.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNone of these additional customer requirements individually erode safety
default, nor do they 
defaultconflict with regulations, but as a whole they introduce 
defaultcomplexities 
defaultto an operator’s Operations Manual. 
defaultPotential areas for improvement include a move to a single set of high standards and more common audit processes.
default A 
defaultmore joined-up approach would improve clarity and reduce complexity.  The UK CAA is centrally positioned to be able to help drive this effort.
default&#xa0;
default3.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAnother example of where the UK CAA could contribute to driving standards further still
default is through the already valued
default work of its Helicopter Safety Research Management Committee, 
defaultthe profile and scope of which could be increased
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSafety starts in our own procurement of aircraft; we expect safety excellence and innovation from helicopter manufacturers. The North Sea is served by a mixed fleet including AgustaWestland, Eurocopter, 
defaultand 
defaultSikorsky.
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEach operator manages operational safety using integrated Safety Management Systems (SMS). In 2012, a regulatory requirement to have an SMS was introduced in the UK although we had implemented SMS long before the requirement was introduced.  The SMS 
defaultis 
defaultused to manage Safety Policy, Safety Risk Management, Safety Assurance and Safety Promotion.
default&#xa0;
default4.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEach operator also employs Safety and Quality teams 
defaultto 
defaultdevelop and implement comprehensive internal quality
default and safety programmes agreed by the UK CAA. 
defaultOur operations are overseen by the CAA through processes including approval of operating and maintenance manuals
default and 
defaultinternal audit programmes.  The CAA also participates in our monthly safety review boards.
